    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and kept seeing stuff about lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles and how the body gets rid of it after a set? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! During a high-intensity workout, your muscles create lactic acid as a by-product of anaerobic respiration, which occurs when oxygen levels are low. This happens when your body can’t get enough oxygen to meet energy demands, so it starts breaking down glucose for fuel. The body then uses lactic acid for energy, but it can also build up in the muscles, causing fatigue and soreness. After a workout, your body gradually gets rid of the lactic acid through the bloodstream, then into the liver and kidneys, and eventually it's converted into glucose or excreted by the kidneys. This whole process helps clear the lactic acid and aids in recovery.",
